                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d643">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7743: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-03T21:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 3, 1944—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 3—5:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>233. Minister [of] Finance has presented Chinese counterproposals which in effect
                    provide that for each U. S. dollar we shall receive 20 dollars CN at official
                    rate and China will add 10 additional dollars CN which shall be credited as
                    reverse lend-lease. I informed Kung that while his proposal would be reported to
                    Washington I was certain that it could not be considered reasonable or
                    satisfactory and that while we are prepared to enter into reverse lend-lease
                    agreement it seems useless to do so unless such agreement is implemented by a
                    reasonable and realistic financial arrangement along lines contemplated in our
                    proposals. This refers to our 189 of January 29; a more detailed report will
                    follow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
